Subject: [PATCH] nvme-pci: try PCIe FLR when controller disable/shutdown hangs (5.10)

The kernel upstream patch ("nvme-pci: try function level reset on
init failure") only attempts a PCIe Function Level Reset when the
controller fails to disable from inside nvme_pci_configure_admin_queue()
(the reset_work path).  However, nvme_disable_ctrl() / nvme_shutdown_ctrl()
are also called from nvme_disable_admin_queue() via nvme_dev_disable(),
which is the first thing nvme_timeout() does for a hung admin or I/O
command:

    nvme_timeout()
      -> nvme_dev_disable(dev, false)
           -> nvme_disable_admin_queue(dev, false)
                -> nvme_disable_ctrl(&dev->ctrl)          <-- can hang
      -> nvme_reset_ctrl(&dev->ctrl)

When the controller is wedged the first nvme_disable_ctrl() times out
with

    nvme nvme0: Device not ready; aborting reset, CSTS=0x1

but nvme_disable_admin_queue() ignores the failure (returns void) and
nvme_dev_disable() proceeds to pci_disable_device().  Depending on
firmware behaviour the subsequent reset_work may not reach the 0304
patched nvme_pci_configure_admin_queue() site (e.g. pci_enable_device_mem()
now fails, or CSTS reads back as -1), so the FLR fallback is never tried
and the device is left needing a power cycle.

Safety:
  - nvme_dev_disable() only calls nvme_disable_admin_queue() when the
    device is present, error_state is normal, CSTS.CFS==0 and
    CSTS.RDY==1 (i.e. !dead) -- exactly the "stuck controller" case
    where FLR is appropriate.
  - pci_save_state() was already done by nvme_pci_enable(), so
    pci_restore_state() after FLR is correct.
  - After FLR the controller is in its reset state (CC==0,
    CSTS.RDY==0); the remainder of nvme_dev_disable() (suspend queues,
    pci_free_irq_vectors, pci_disable_device) is unaffected.
  - On a subsequent reset_work, nvme_pci_configure_admin_queue()'s
    nvme_disable_ctrl() will succeed immediately, so the 0304 FLR path
    will not double-FLR.

pcie_reset_flr() is provided by the 0304 patch (backported from upstream
into drivers/pci/pci.c and declared in include/linux/pci.h), so this
patch only touches drivers/nvme/host/pci.c.

Signed-off-by: Local backport <kernel@local>
---
diff -Nur a/drivers/nvme/host/pci.c b/drivers/nvme/host/pci.c
--- a/drivers/nvme/host/pci.c
+++ b/drivers/nvme/host/pci.c
@@ -1421,11 +1421,34 @@
 static void nvme_disable_admin_queue(struct nvme_dev *dev, bool shutdown)
 {
 	struct nvme_queue *nvmeq = &dev->queues[0];
+	int result;
 
 	if (shutdown)
-		nvme_shutdown_ctrl(&dev->ctrl);
+		result = nvme_shutdown_ctrl(&dev->ctrl);
 	else
-		nvme_disable_ctrl(&dev->ctrl);
+		result = nvme_disable_ctrl(&dev->ctrl);
+
+	if (result < 0) {
+		struct pci_dev *pdev = to_pci_dev(dev->dev);
+
+		/*
+		 * The NVMe Controller did not respond to a normal
+		 * disable or shutdown.  Use the lower level and bigger
+		 * hammer PCIe Function Level Reset to bring the device
+		 * back to its initial state so any subsequent reset
+		 * work has a chance to succeed.
+		 */
+		result = pcie_reset_flr(pdev, false);
+		if (result == 0) {
+			pci_restore_state(pdev);
+			dev_info(dev->ctrl.device,
+				 "controller %s completed after pcie flr\n",
+				 shutdown ? "shutdown" : "disable");
+		} else {
+			dev_warn(dev->ctrl.device,
+				 "pcie flr fallback failed (%d)\n", result);
+		}
+	}
 
 	nvme_poll_irqdisable(nvmeq);
 }
-- 
